Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]},{"name":"Margery","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual medieval vernacular form of   Margaret   (now also commonly spelled   Marjorie  ). This form of the name is preserved in the nursery rhyme ‘See-saw, Margery Daw’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":18,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Margaret Margery 17th D'Olney was born in 1364, in Olney, Buckinghamshire, England. She married Lord John de  Olney III about 1387, in Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died about 1443, in Weston Underwood, Buckinghamshire, England, at the age of 80."},"et":{"1364–about 1443":"1364–umbes 1443","1354–1419":"1354–1419","1394–1453":"1394–1453","1405–Female":"1405–Surnud","1364–1443":"1364–1443","1443":"1443","1453":"1453","1354":"1354","1364":"1364","Abt. 1387":"umbes 1387","1394":"1394","about 1443":"umbes 1443","1382":"1382","1419":"1419","1390":"1394","1405":"1405","Tachebrook, Olney, Buckinghamshire, England":"Olney, Buckinghamshire, England","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","Weston Underwood, Buckinghamshire, England":"Weston Underwood, Buckinghamshire, England","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1364–about 1443":"1364–noin 1443","1354–1419":"1354–1419","1394–1453":"1394–1453","1405–Female":"1405–Kuollut","1364–1443":"1364–1443","